        <h3>App Build</h3>
        <p>
          The KnowBetter app is built on a MVC app using Entity Framework. The Server Database for the app uses linked tables to save all the data. We
          also use an API call to display ingredient data when the user clicks on a product's ingredient. The app and the database are both hosted 
          separately on Azure.
        </p>
        <h3>Current/Future Features</h3>
        <p>
          KnowBetter allows users to search a list of cosmetic ingredients, add ingredients to a list of favorites or a list of items to avoid. 
          Users are able to search a database of products, and compare a product's ingredients to their list of favorites or items to avoid. 
          It will eventually include user-submitted ingredients and products as well.
        </p>
        <h3>Team Dynamics</h3>
        <p>
          As a team we managed our code using GitHub for merge management and version control.  We created a kanban board on GitHub and assigned
          tasks to each team member and the tasks would be linked to our individual pull requests and the tasks would be automatically completed
          once the pull request was approved.
        </p>
        <h3>My contribution</h3>
        <img src="../images/contribution.jpg" class ="PortImg" alt="code contribution">
        <p>
          For this project I was tasked with Creating the following Views: Ingredient Library, Dashboard, Edit Profile, Avoid Ingredient, & Favorite Ingredient.
          I also went through on the final version and cleaned up all unnecessary code that was in our app. The portion I struggled with the most was Creating the
          Flexbox CSS for the Avoid/Favorite View for delete buttons. I eventually discovered I had the main container inside of our loop so it was creating 
          multiple container with a single container inside instead one one container with multiple containers inside.  The other issue I faced with this app was
          learning the framework and how to use it since this is the second MVC app I have helped to build.  Other than the code contributions I also was in charge
          of weekly documentation for 3 weeks and I assisted with testing.
        </p>
        <h3>Overall Experience</h3>
        <p>
          From this experience I learned that I need to spend more time coding with a database because I was having issues early on with getting the delete button in
          avoid ingredients working. This experience has made me want to learn more programming platforms so I can migrate a project onto a new platform if 
          I wanted to.  What I've learned is that I have a lot more growing to do as a programmer but also that I can adapt to platforms I haven't had much experience
          with. From finishing this project I learned how to better utilize divs as containers as have formatted as such in CSS. I never really understood CSS much
          before this app and I definitely feel like I have a much better grasp on CSS now. If I were to recommend anything to someone attempting a similar app it would
          be to leave most of the CSS and styling until the very end because there were so many times we were changing around the way we were calling
          the CSS files and the layout.  I also would say to spend more time learning the platform that you are going to use because there's so many little things built 
          into these platforms that normally go unused due to lack of knowledge.
        </p>
